        {/* CATEGORY 1: General Questions */}
        <div class="block">
          <h3 class="text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-neutral-500 font-mono mb-6 pb-2 border-b border-neutral-200">
            General Questions
          </h3>
          <div class="space-y-6">
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-800 mb-1.5 text-sm">What is the difference between a network address and a broadcast address?</h4>
              <p class="text-xs text-neutral-500 leading-relaxed text-justify">
                <strong>Network Address:</strong> The very first IP in a subnet range; it identifies the specific network itself and cannot be assigned to devices.<br />
                <strong>Broadcast Address:</strong> The very last IP in a subnet range; it is used to send data simultaneously to all devices within that network.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-800 mb-1.5 text-sm">What is CIDR notation?</h4>
              <p class="text-xs text-neutral-500 leading-relaxed text-justify">
                CIDR notation is a compact way to represent an IP address and its associated routing prefix. For example, 192.168.1.0/24 means the first 24 bits of the 32-bit IP address represent the network.
              </p>
            </div>
<div>
  <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-800 mb-1.5 text-sm">What is the formula for usable hosts in a subnet?</h4>
  <p class="text-xs text-neutral-500 leading-relaxed text-justify">
    The mathematical formula is 2<sup>32 - n</sup> - 2, where "n" represents the CIDR network prefix suffix value. The two subtracted addresses account for the unassignable network base address and the broadcast limit interface boundaries.
  </p>
</div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-800 mb-1.5 text-sm">What makes this a visual subnet calculator alternative?</h4>
              <p class="text-xs text-neutral-500 leading-relaxed text-justify">
                Unlike legacy online calculators bogged down by ads, this tool features an interactive tree visualizer. It maps out equal subnet blocks below your selection, letting network architects click to split allocations down to micro-subnet layers reactively.
              </p>
