          <h3 class="text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-neutral-500 font-mono mb-6 pb-2 border-b border-neutral-200">
            Troubleshooting &amp; Best Practices
          </h3>
          <div class="space-y-6">
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-800 mb-1.5 text-sm">Why do some subnets have exactly the same IP range but different CIDR notations?</h4>
              <p class="text-xs text-neutral-500 leading-relaxed text-justify">
                Larger parent networks require smaller CIDR prefixes (e.g., a /24 provides 256 addresses). When subnets break down into smaller units, the prefix increments (e.g., splitting a /24 results in multiple /25 subnets containing 128 addresses each).
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-800 mb-1.5 text-sm">Is this CIDR subnet calculator online tool safe for internal enterprise architectures?</h4>
              <p class="text-xs text-neutral-500 leading-relaxed text-justify">
                100% yes. The math calculation logic executes completely inside your browser engine's local thread context (V8 runtime sandbox). No infrastructure topologies, private network addresses, or AWS VPC configurations ever cross network hooks, making it completely secure for high-compliance engineering environments.
              </p>
