        {/* CATEGORY 3: Usage & Implementation */}
        <div class="block pt-6">
          <h3 class="text-sm font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-neutral-500 font-mono mb-6 pb-2 border-b border-neutral-200">
            Usage &amp; Implementation
          </h3>
          <div class="space-y-6">
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-800 mb-1.5 text-sm">How are CIDR calculators used in cloud computing?</h4>
              <p class="text-xs text-neutral-500 leading-relaxed text-justify">
                Network engineers use them to design VPCs (Virtual Private Clouds) in AWS, Azure, or GCP. They help ensure that subnets don't overlap, which would cause severe packet loss or routing conflicts.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-800 mb-1.5 text-sm">What tools can I use to calculate CIDR ranges?</h4>
              <p class="text-xs text-neutral-500 leading-relaxed text-justify">
                You can calculate subnets quickly using free, web-based tools like the CIDR.xyz Interactive Tool or UptimeRobot IP Subnet Calculator.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-800 mb-1.5 text-sm">How do I use this as an IP subnet calculator download version for offline use?</h4>
              <p class="text-xs text-neutral-500 leading-relaxed text-justify">
                Because all parsing engines run fully client-side inside local browser memory sandbox frameworks, you can simply hit save (Ctrl+S or Cmd+S) to store the entire static bundle. Disconnect your networking interface entirely, and the local transformation engine will continue executing perfectly with zero network footprint.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div>
              <h4 class="font-bold text-neutral-800 mb-1.5 text-sm">Can I use this module as a CIDR split calculator?</h4>
              <p class="text-xs text-neutral-500 leading-relaxed text-justify">
                Yes. By using the integrated interactive map section, you can drill directly down into subnets. Clicking any generated layout quadrant automatically applies the split math to isolate equal blocks with individual routing parameters.
